Winemaking Research

Sulfur Dioxide [mg/L]: is added to preserve wine due to its antimicrobial properties. It is also a product of fermentation. Total sulfer dioxide is free + bound, where bound sulfur dioxide has exhausted its preservative usefulness and bound to sugars, acetaldehyde, and phenolic compounds.

Acidity [g/L]: Acids change the pH of the wine, cut the taste of sugar, and enhance the effectiveness of sulfur dioxides. Fixed acidity refers to Tantric acid, Volatile acidity mainly refers to Acetic acid, and Citric acidity of course refers to citric acid. It is desired to have a balance of acidity and sweetness (residual sugar).

Residual Sugar [g/L]: lends sweetness to wine (cuts dryness). Sugar is a reagent in the fermentation process by which yeast produces alcohol.

Chlorates [g/L]: refers to Sodium Chloride, analogous to salt in wines.

Sulphates [g/L]: refers to Potassium Sulphate.

Density: Alcohol is less dense than sugar, therefore as sugar is consumed during fermentation and alcohol is produced, the density goes down.

Bivariate Plots

I will start with a scatter matrix, comparing all variables against one another and calculating correlation coefficients in one step.

It is necessary to zoom in on this plot in a new window in order to use it. See the attached wineQuality_scatter.png for details. The scatterplot matrix is useful because it immediately reveals relationships between all variable pairs in a dataframe, while also yielding line plot histograms of each solo variable. For instance, we can see that fixed acidity has a nice normal curve, white citric acidity is bimodal. Chlorides appears normal with a few high outliers, and resigual sugars is left skewed. The plots I am most interested in are on the last line, which are each variable versusquality. No individual variable has a strong correlation with quality, but density and alcohol do appear to have some weak correlation.

I will first look at density versus quality with two plots.

Here we see the relationship between density in two plots. As I hypothesized, there appears to be a weak relationship between density and quality. From my research I know that a low density is associated with a high alcohol content, so I will look to see if the same behavior exists with alcohol content.

As expected, higher alcohol content does appear to be associated with higher quality ratings. The first chart may be more revealing than the second in that we see a few higher quality ratings even though the number of high alcohol content samples is lower! Another way of visualizing this relationship is with a boxplot, as follows.

This plot shows more clearly the relationship between alcohol and quality, although it misses the information about the distribution of quality. Starting the worst quality wine, as we move up in quality the median alcohol content drops by about 1% ABV until the wine reaches a quality of 6, where the ABV rises to 12.5% ABV at a quality of 9.

One more relationship that was revealed by the scatter matrix was a strong correlation (0.84) between residual sugar and density.

It should not be surprising that as residual sugar rises, so does density, as sugar is what is consumed in the fermentation process to produce alcohol, and alcohol has a low density.

Next I will see if I can flesh out more complex relationships, particularly relating to quality

Multivariate Plots

The scatter matrix showed that none of the variables for acidity had a strong relationship directly with quality, but I might be able to derive on if I can find a relationship between those supporting variables themselves. I know that pH is a measure of acidity, so I would expect the pH variable to correlate somehow with the amount of acid in a wine.

As expected, we see that as total acidity increases, pH decreases slightly. There does not appear to be any correlation between pH and quality, or acidity and quality. Total Acidity is affected primarily by fixed acidity, and very little by volatile or citric acidity.

I would also expect there to be a relationship between free and total sulfur dioxide. I will repeat the above colored scatter plot for total.sulfur.dioxide and free.sulfur.dioxide versus quality.

There appears to be a ‘sweet spot’ for free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide where one area between 30-50 mg/L free sulfur dioxide and 75-125 mg/L total sulfur dioxide has a higher density of 7+ quality ratings. I will indlude these variables in a model I make later to see if they lend themselves to predicting quality because of this.

The strongest correlation between any two variables on the scatter matrix was between density and residual sugar, which makes sense because as sugar is consumed by the fermentation process it will be converted into alcohol, which has a lower density. Knowing this, I will see if there is any correlation between density and residual.sugar vs quality.

Here we finally see a complex relationship. As expected, as residual sugar rises, so does density. But what we also see is that if we hold residual sugar constant and raise the density, quality goes down. This could imply that there is a imbalance in sugar and alcohol, resulting in a wine that is too sweet. Let’s try repeating the plot with alcohol instead of density to see what that yields.

This plot shows what we saw before, that higher alcohol contents are often rated higher quality. But it does not reveal any deeper trends other than that very few wines have both high residual sugar and high alcohol content.

Evidently, the linear model does a very poor job of fitting the dataset. The correlation coefficient using 6 variables was only .229. Interestingly, the best predictor remained to be alcohol, which has a .190 correlation coefficient by itself.

Multivariate Analysis

The primary relationships observed in the multivariate cases were those between density, alcohol, residual sugar, and quality. As expected, alcohol is inversely correlated with density, which is positively correlated with residual sugar. The relationship I was not expecting was between free and total sulphur dioxide and quality, where there appeared to be a ‘sweet spot’ for quality. Again this could have to do with a ‘balance’ of some kind, or it could be related to some other variable which I did not investigate.

The 6 degree linear model I created did a very poor job fitting the quality variable, which suggests that even among variables that exhibited some kind of a relationship with quality, the relationship is nonlinear or incomplete.

Final Plots and Summary

First Plot

Description 1

This plot shows the median and IQR of alcohol content per quality rating, and I have also added the count of samples per rating to each box. It is evident that the highest rated wines have the highest alcohol content, but that the opposite end of the scale also shows a lift in alcohol ratings, possibly because the lowest end wines are intended to be strong if not tasty. Meanwhile the high end options are ones that can blend taste with strength. Or perhaps the raters just rate higher when they are inebriated.

Second Plot

Description 2

Here we see a relationship that is only clear on a 3 variable plot like this one. Density and residual sugar are both correlated with quality, but only when the other is held constant, because density and residual sugar are also positively correlated with one another. My interpretation of this plot is that for a given amount of residual sugar, removing alcohol (and raising density) will yield a wine that is too sweet, lowering its quality rating.

Third Plot

Description 3

This plot shows the relationship of total and free sulfur dioxide. As expected, total sulfur dioxide rises with free sulfur dioxide. What is interesting about this plot is that there is a ‘sweet spot’ in terms of wine quality right in the middle of the plot. It is unclear to me why this is, and I was not able to uncover strong relationships between sulfur and other variables in this dataset, so that is something that I would like to investigate further in the future.

Reflection

This was a challenging dataset, because as was made clear by the scatter matrix, there are very few ostensible correlations between individual variables. Through some pseudo-random experimentation I was able to flesh out some interesting interactions, particularly relating to density, alcohol, residual sugar, total and free sulfur dioxide, and quality, but I was not able to tie them all together in an effective model. What was surprising to me was that of all variables, it seems that alcohol content by itself was easily the best predictor of quality. It would have been useful to have more info on wines beyond chemical composition, such as year, vineyard, price etc. Without more info to go on, my best advice when wine shopping is just to buy the strong stuff. According to this dataset, if you aim for >= 12.8% ABV, you are more likely than not to get above average quality wine!
